00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:15.790
Good.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:18.130
So now I have a second
charge-- a test charge which

00:01:18.130 --> 00:01:20.440
is moving with the velocity u.

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:23.320
That test charge will
experience the magnetic force.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:26.050
The force is equal to
the test charge itself,

00:01:26.050 --> 00:01:29.650
qt, times u cross
B, the velocity

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:33.310
cross the magnetic field.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:35.080
So there's clearly
a magnetic force

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:39.160
acting on this [INAUDIBLE]
charge in this reference frame.

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:42.730
However, if I now move
into a reference frame

00:01:42.730 --> 00:01:46.130
where the source
charge is stationary,

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:49.020
a stationary charge is not
creating magnetic field,

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:50.240
so the magnetic field is 0.

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:54.400
Hence the magnetic force
on the test charge is 0.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.880
I can, alternatively, look at
the reference frame in which

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:00.100
the test charge is stationary.

00:02:00.100 --> 00:02:03.040
And so also here,
because u is equal to 0,

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:05.450
the magnetic force is 0.

00:02:05.450 --> 00:02:10.150
So clearly, we do have to treat
magnetic and electric fields

00:02:10.150 --> 00:02:12.370
in sort of a
consistent manner as we

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:15.340
treated time and space,
and energy momentum

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:16.930
in a consistent manner.

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:19.660
But we need a concept of
electromagnetic fields.

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:22.540
And previously in this class, we
looked at electromagnetic field

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:25.622
light before.

00:02:25.622 --> 00:02:28.080
The difference here is-- and
