energy, and time and space.

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:04.870
And Lorentz transformation
looks very similar.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:08.670
So we can, motivated
by this, write

00:05:08.670 --> 00:05:14.110
a 4 vector, which is the first
component c times the density.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:19.200
And as the first, second, and
third component, the current.

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:21.450
And you find that
the invariant here

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:26.160
is very similar to time and
space, energy and momentum

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:31.015
given as the density where
the charges are addressed.

00:05:31.015 --> 00:05:34.160
And that's the invariant,
and you can calculate this

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:41.140
from multiplying the 4 vector
[INAUDIBLE] square [INAUDIBLE]..

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:43.520
So concept questions.

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:47.330
Is the electric charge conserved
in the Lorentz transformation,

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:49.190
or did we actually
change the charge?

00:05:49.190 --> 00:05:52.430
So we have the charge density
here and the current here,

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:54.320
but did we actually
change the charge

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:57.420
on the Lorentz [INAUDIBLE]?

00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:59.170
The answer is, no, we
did not change them,

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:01.780
so the charge is conserved.

00:06:01.780 --> 00:06:06.540
The charge is invariant in
the Lorentz transformation.

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:10.790
Is electric current conserved
in Lorentz transformation,

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:12.830
or invariant on the
Lorentz transformation?

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:15.290
Should rather use
invariant [INAUDIBLE]..

00:06:15.290 --> 00:06:16.680
And the answer is, no, it's not.

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:18.560
So we have seen from
the very first example

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:20.840
